{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519480"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.37,0.33,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15286"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents seeking advice. Her 40-year-old sister has recently been diagnosed with gastric cancer and because of her young age, she underwent genetic counselling. She has been found to have a CDH1 mutation and this younger sister has the same mutation. This patient is fit and well and does not have any digestive tract symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be recommended to the patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance only","Regular monitoring of CEA and CA19-9 levels","Yearly endoscopic screening starting now","Yearly endoscopic screening starting at age of 35","Total gastrectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECDH1 is a tumour suppressor gene which protects against the development of gastric cancer. Mutations in the CDH1 gene confer high risk for developing hereditary diffuse gastric cancer (HDGC), a malignancy which is often diagnosed at late stages and has a poor prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECDH1 mutations also lead to a high risk (40%) of developing lobular breast carcinoma in women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeople with the mutation and a family history of stomach cancer have a very high chance of developing the cancer. Some 2% of all gastric cancers are hereditary diffuse gastric cancers. Is is estimated that the lifetime risk is between 60-80% by the age of 80, the risk being higher in women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe only way to reliably prevent the development of the cancer is through a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal gastrectomy. \u003C/strong\u003EAlthough the procedure has significant side effects, including nutritional deficiencies, diarrhoea, and weight loss, it is recommended given the high rates of mortality associated with invasive disease. Total gastrectomy is recommended due to the poor uptake with current screening tests. Endoscopy is random and CT not good enough. This is opposed to lobular breast cancer, where magnetic resonance imaging is recommended for screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the high risk of developing HDGC, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is not sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDGC forms diffuse, signet-ring shaped cells that are difficult to visualise on endoscopy prior to becoming an invasive malignancy, meaning most patients are diagnosed at a late stage. As such, there is no reliable screening test available, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Escreening \u003C/strong\u003Epoor options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003ECEA \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003ECA19-9 \u003C/strong\u003Eare tumour markers involved in gastric cancer, they are of insufficient specificity and sensitivity to be used as reliable screening tests.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mutations in the CDH1 gene lead to a high risk of developing hereditary diffuse gastric cancer, which confers a poor prognosis.","Total gastrectomy is the only reliable way to prevent HDGC given difficulties diagnosing the cancer on endoscopy and lack of sensitive, specific blood tests."],"references":["van der Post RS, Vogelaar IP, Carneiro F, Guilford P, Huntsman D, Hoogerbrugge N, et al. Hereditary diffuse gastric cancer: updated clinical guideines with an emphasis on germline CDH1 mutation carriers. J. Med. Genet. 2015 Jun 13;52:361-374.","Benesch MGK, Bursey SR, O\u0027Connell AC, Ryan MG, Howard CL, Stockley CC, et al. CDH1 Gene Mutation Hereditary Diffuse Gastric Cancer Outcomes: Analysis of a Large Cohort, Systematic Review of Endoscopic Surveillance, and Secondary Cancer Risk Postulation. Cancers. 2021 Jun;13(11):2622."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-06T14:20:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T12:21:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gas